eighborhoods, Greenwich Village, which--thanks to cultural icons such as Eugene O'Neill, Isadora Duncan, and Emma Goldman--became a symbol of social and intellectual freedom. Stansell eloquently explains how the mixing of old and new worlds, politics and art, and radicalism and commerce so characteristic of New York shaped the modern American urban scene. American Moderns is both an examination and a celebration of a way of life that's been nearly forgotten.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aBohemianismzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryx20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAfrican Americans (blacks).  aAmerican (magazine).  aAnderson, Margaret.  aAnglo-Saxonism.  aBabette.  aBeat movement.  aBercovici, Naomi.  aBloomsbury group.  aBryant, Louise.  aCivil War.  aCommercial Advertiser.  aCommunists.  aDadaists.  aDecadents.  aDuncan, Isadora.  aEaster Rebellion (1916).  aEternal Feminine.  aFerrer Center.  aFree Speech League.  aGogol.  aGreenwich Village.  aHagar Revelly (novel).  aHarlem Renaissance.  aHaymarket massacre.  aHiggins, Michael.  aImagism.  aImpressionists.  aIrish immigrants.  aJews.  aKipling, Rudyard.  aLippincott’s Monthly.  aLittle Review.  aMarxism.  aMcKinley assassination.  aModern Library.  aNo-Conscription League.  aPaterson Pageant.  aRodman, Henrietta.  abourgeois culture.  acensorship.  acooperative housekeeping.  ademocracy.  afeminism.  afree expression.  ahuman-interest writing.  aimmigrants.  ajournalism.  alabor movement.  aliterature.  amisogyny.  aradicalism and radicals.  aself realization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe